Abstract:  Organocatalysis  is  widely  used  for  the  asymmetric  synthesis  of  natural  products  and  pharmaceuticals,  and  bifunctional  organocatalysts  are  particularly  effective  for  controlling  stereochemistry.    Here,  we  present  an  overview  of  involving  bifunctional  catalysts  natural  products  syntheses  bearing a hydrogen-bonding donor moiety reported during the last  five years.  Natural  products  are  prolific  resources  for  drug  discovery;  approximately  half  of  all  small-molecular  pharmaceuticals  approved  during  1981–2014  originated  from  natural  products.[1]   Organic  synthesis  plays  a  critical  role  in  generating  drug  leads,  both  from  natural  products  and  from  compounds  discovered  in  chemical  libraries.[2]  In  particular,  organocatalysis  is  a  powerful  tool for the efficient asymmetric synthesis of complex molecules  in an environmentally friendly manner,[3] and bifunctional catalysts  are especially effective for controlling the stereochemistry of the  product.[4]  In bifunctional catalysts, two different functional groups  act synergistically to bring nucleophiles and electrophiles close to  each other, while controlling the stereochemistry in the transition  state, while simultaneously increasing the reactivity (Figure 1a). b) Representative Hydrogen Bonding Donor Functional Group a) Acrtivation Mode of Bifunctional Organocatalyst Hydrogen-bonding  interaction  is  frequently  employed  in  this  type of catalysis.  For example, hydroxyl group, amide, (thio)urea,  squaramide and guanidinium ion are typically used as hydrogen- bonding  donor  functional  groups  (Figure  1b),  forming  hydrogen  bonds  to  a  Lewis-basic  moiety  in  the  substrate  via  their  acidic  protons.  Numerous chiral bifunctional organocatalysis have been  developed in the past decade and used in the synthesis of natural  products  as  well  as  pharmaceuticals.[5]    Here,  we  provide  an  overview  of  natural  products  synthesis  involving  asymmetric  organocatalysis,  especially  focusing  on  bifunctional  catalysts  bearing  a  hydrogen-bonding  donor  group,  reported  during  the  past five years.  1. (Thio)urea-type bifunctional organocatalysts  2-1.  Synthesis of Apocynaceae hydrocarbazole alkaloids by  Fan’s group

A  functionalized  hydrocarbazole  motif  is  seen  in  many  natural  products.  Among them, Apocynaceae hydrocarbazole alkaloids  have become attractive targets for synthetic chemists due to their  interesting  structure  and  biological  properties.[6]    In  2015,  the  Apocynaceae  hydrocarbazole  alkaloids  (+)-deethylbophyllidine  (5)  and  (+)-limaspermidine  (6)  were  efficiently  synthesized  via  organocatalysis  by  Fan  and  co-workers  (Scheme  1).[7]    In  that  work,  a  tandem  aminolysis/aza-Michael  reaction  of  spirocyclic  para-dienoneimide 2 with allylamine, catalyzed by amine-thiourea  bifunctional  corresponding  hydrocarbazole  3  with  the  required  A/B/C-ring  system  together  with the all-carbon quaternary stereocenter of 5 and 6, with high  enantioselectivity.   In this organocatalytic reaction, the thiourea  and  amine  moieties  in  1  were  proposed  to  hydrogen-bond  with  the carbonyl group of enone and carbamate, respectively, so that  nucleophilic  attack  of  carbamate  takes  place  from  the  Re  face.   Then,  the  second  intramolecular  aza-Michael  reaction  of  3  proceeded  upon  treatment  with  sodium  hydroxide  to  give  tetracyclic  hydrocarbazole  4  (85%  yield),  leading  to  the  total  synthesis  of  (+)-deethylbophyllidine  (5)  and  (+)-limaspermidine  (6).    (+)-deethylbophyllidine (5) 2-2. Synthesis of (+)-trigolutes B by Gong’s group

Trigolutesin  B  (13),  which  shows  weak  acetylcholinesterase- inhibitory  activity,  was  isolated  from  Trigonostemon  lutescens  together with five structurally related congeners.[8]  Gong and co- workers reported the first total synthesis of trigolutesin B (13) in  2015  (Scheme  2).[9]    They  employed  an  enantioselective  conjugate  addition  reaction  of  3-(1-tosylalkyl)indoles  9  with  thiourea  oxindole  8  bifunctional  organocatalyst  7.    High  enantioselectivity  (98%  ee)  was obtained by utilizing potassium carbonate (1.1 equiv.) as a  base  at  room  temperature.    This  organocatalytic  reaction  was  proposed to proceed as follows: a vinylogous imine intermediate  generated from 9 with a base is activated by the thiourea moiety  in  7  through  a  double  hydrogen-bonding  interaction,  while  the  tertiary amine in 7 promotes the tautomerization of oxindole 8 to  enol form.  Then, nucleophilic addition of 8 generates 10 efficiently  by the dual activation of both nucleophile and electrophile with the  bifunctional  organocatalyst  7.    Total  synthesis  of  trigolutesin  B  (13)  was  accomplished  from  10  by  constructing  the  C  ring,  followed by demethylation with BBr3.  Scheme 2. 2-3. Synthesis of (–)-haliclonin A by Huang’s group

(–)-Haliclonin A (27), isolated from a marine sponge, Haliclona sp.,  by  Shin  and  co-workers,  is  a  unique  macrocyclic  alkaloid  containing a characteristic 3-azabicyclononane structure; it shows  moderate antibacterial activity and cytotoxicity.[10]  A challenging  issue  in  the  synthesis  of  (–)-haliclonin  A  (27)  is  the  asymmetric  construction  of  the  all-carbon  quaternary  stereocenter  at  C6  (Scheme  3).  Huang  and  co-workers  examined  enantioselective  conjugate addition of nitromethane to enone 15 in the presence  of  amine-thiourea  bifunctional  organocatalyst  14  (20  mol%),  obtaining the conjugate addition product 16 in 80% yield with 97%  ee.[11]  In this reaction, nitromethane, a nucleophile, was used as  the solvent (Scheme 3).  In this organocatalytic reaction, iminium  formation takes place first between the amine in 14 and enone 15,  and  nucleophilic  attack  of  nitromethane  occurs  via  hydrogen- bonding  interaction  with  the  thiourea  moiety  in  14,  enabling  efficient construction of the stereochemistry at C6 in 27.  Then,  construction  of  the  3-azabicyclononane  skeleton  17  in  27  was  achieved by Pd-mediated cyclization of 16,[12] and aldol reaction  of  aldehyde  18  with  17  followed  by  ring-closing  metathesis  reaction of 19 with Grubbs 1st catalyst afforded 20, having an aza- macrocyclic structure.  Two alkyne side chains were introduced  into 20 at N8 and C1, and the resulting diyne 23 was subjected to  ring-closing  metathesis  reaction  under  Fürstner’s  conditions  to  give 24.[13]  Desulfonylation of 24 was carried out by reaction with

introduced  into 20 at N8 and C1, and the resulting diyne 23 was subjected to  ring-closing  metathesis  reaction  under  Fürstner’s  conditions  to  give 24.[13]  Desulfonylation of 24 was carried out by reaction with  Mg in methanol, and the formyl group was introduced on nitrogen  to  give  25.  After  oxidation  with  AZADO  at  C1  to  provide  26,[14]  desilylation  tris(dimethylamino)sulfonium  with  difluorotrimethylsilicate (TASF) afforded (–)-haliclonin A (27).

2-4. Synthesis of Clavine alkaloids by Bisai’s group  The clavine alkaloids are a subclass of the indole-containing ergot  family.    They  show  agonistic  or  antagonistic  activities  towards  neuroreceptors of dopamine, serotonin, and adrenaline, and they  are regarded as potential drug candidates for related disorders.[15]   Biosynthetically, the C-ring in clavine alkaloids is constructed by  decarboxylative C-C bond-forming reaction between C5 and C10,  and synthetic studies of these molecules have followed the same  strategy.[16]   i. TMSI, HMDS j. AcOH, SiO2 k. AZADO+BF4 In  2018,  Bisai  and  co-workers  reported  comprehensive  total  syntheses  of  seco-agroclavine  (32),  chanoclavine  I  aldehyde  (33),  pyrcolavine  (34)  and  festuclavine  (35)  based  upon  this  biomimetic  strategy  (Scheme  4).[17]    They  employed  organocatalytic  enantio-  and  diastereoselective  intramolecular Michael reaction of nitroalkane to construct the C  ring in 31-35.  They used cinchona-derived thiourea bifunctional  organocatalyst  28  (10  mol%)  to  convert  indole  29  to  the  g- nitroester 30, which was obtained in 93% yield with 97% ee.  They  proposed that nitronate moiety in 29 is stabilized by thiourea, and  oxygen  in  the  ester  group  interacts  with  N-H  of  the  ammonium  moiety  of  quinuclidine.    The  clavine  alkaloids  31-35  were  efficiently synthesized from the key common intermediate 30.  Scheme 4. Synthesis of clavine alkaloids by Bisai’s group.  2-5. Synthesis of pyrroloindoline alkaloids by Bisai’s group

Hexahydropyrrolo[2,3-b]indoles  (HPIs)  constitute  one  of  the  largest families of indole alkaloids.  These natural products exhibit  a broad spectrum of biological activities,, including anticancer and  antibacterial  activities.[18]    Bisai’s  group  has  explored  synthetic  studies  of  HPIs  based  upon  organocatalytic  reactions.    They  employed enantioselective aldol reaction of oxindole derivatives  to construct the characteristic all-carbon quaternary stereogenic  center at the C3 position in HPIs.[19]  In the presence of cinchona- derived  thiourea  bifunctional  organocatalyst  36,  formaldehyde  was  reacted  with  oxindole  37  to  obtain  the  corresponding  aldol  product  38  with  high  enantioselectivity  (Scheme  5).    In  the  reaction,  enolate  37  is  proposed  to  interact  with  N-H  of  the  ammonium moiety in quinuclidine, and formaldehyde is activated  by thiourea via hydrogen-bonding interaction.  According to their  TS  model,  the  re-face  adduct  is  obtained  stereoselectively.   Based upon this catalytic reaction, they efficiently achieved total  syntheses of a series of HPIs, 39–45.    The same group applied the organocatalytic aldol reaction for  the synthesis of the dimeric HPI alkaloid (+)-folicanthine (57) from  symmetric  bis-oxindole  46.[20]    In  this  reaction,  enantioselective  aldol  reaction  of  46  and  subsequent  translactonization  reaction  proceeded  simultaneously  to  generate  spiro-lactone  47  in  96%  yield with 93% ee (d.r. = 1:1). Synthesis of Kopsia alkaloids by Ma’s group

Kopsia  indole  alkaloids  are  of  synthetic  interest  due  to  their  complex structures and biological activities, including cholinergic,  antirheumatic, and anti-inflammatory effects.[25]  Synthesis of this  class  of  alkaloids  has  been  intensively  explored  for  several  decades,  and  recently,  Ma  and  co-workers  have  succeeded  in  total  synthesis  of  Kopsia  alkaloids  by  utilizing  organocatalysis  (Scheme 8).[26]  They employed asymmetric Michael addition of  N-1-naphthyl-b-keto amide 71 and 2-chloroacrylonitrile (72) in the  presence of 10 mol% of amine thiourea bifunctional catalyst 70,  obtaining  the  3,3-disubstituted  hydrocarbazole  73  in  93%  yield  with 97% ee after removal of the chloro group.  This reaction was  applicable on a practical scale of 9 g in the presence of 5 mol%  catalyst  70  without  decrease  of  the  yield  or  enantioselectivity.   After conversion of 73 to 76, the characteristic caged ring system  of  Kopsia  indole  alkaloids  was  efficiently  constructed  by  radical  oxidative  cyclization  reaction,  utilizing  MnIII  and  CuII  for  single- electron  oxidation.  The  oxidation  products  77  and  78  were  obtained in 76% and 10% yield, respectively.  Total syntheses of  80-82 were achieved from the key intermediate 77. Amaryllidaceae alkaloids have a characteristic hydroquinolinone  motif in the B/C rings with four to six stereogenic centers.  These  alkaloids are interesting synthetic targets due to their complex and  diverse  structures,  as  well  as  their  biological  activities,  which  include  cytotoxicity  towards  several  cancer  cell  lines.[27]    Our  group has reported total synthesis of the Amaryllidaceae alkaloid  (91)  by  applying  asymmetric  (+)-trans-dihydrolycoricidine  organocatalysis  (Scheme  9).[28]  the    For  construction  of  stereochemistry  at  C10b,  we  employed  enantioselective  1,4- Friedel-Crafts (FC) reaction between sesamol (84) and nitro olefin  85  the  presence  of  guanidine-thiourea  bifunctional  organocatalyst 83 to obtain the corresponding 1,4-FC adduct 86  in 93% ee as an inseparable diastereomeric mixture at C2.  The  olefin 86 was converted to aldehyde 87 under oxidative cleavage  conditions,  and  then  intramolecular  Henry  reaction  was  carried  out to give 88 in 48% yield from 87.  The B ring was constructed  by  palladium-catalyzed  intramolecular  CO  insertion  reaction  to  give 88, which was further oxidized regio- and stereoselectively at  the C ring to furnish (+)-trans-dihydrolycoricidine (91). 3-2. Synthesis of (+)-rishirilide B by Nagasawa’s group  (+)-Rishirilide B (99) is an anthracenone-type natural product with  antitumor  activity.[29]    In  2017,  our  group  has  reported  an  enantioselective total synthesis of (+)-rishirilide B (99) by applying  oxidative  kinetic  resolution  catalyzed  by  a  guanidine-urea  bifunctional  organocatalyst  as  a  key  reaction  (Scheme  10).[30,31]   The bifunctional organocatalyst 92 contains urea as a hydrogen- bond  donor,  which  the  oxidant,  cumene  interacts  with  hydroperoxide  (CHP).    In  the  presence  of  catalyst  92,  oxidative  kinetic  resolution  of  b-keto  ester  rac-93  took  place  smoothly,  affording  the  a-hydroxylation  product  of  (–)-94  with  high  enantioselectivity (90% ee, s = 53).  The enantiomeric excess was  increased to 99 % ee by a single recrystallization, and then the  tricyclic skeleton of 98 was constructed by means of Diels-Alder  reaction,  followed  by  isomerization  with  BBr3.    The  synthesis  of  (+)-rishirilide  B  (99)  was  completed  by  deprotection  of  the  tBu  ester group with AlCl3.  As a result, the absolute stereochemistry  of natural rishirilide B (99) was determined to be (2R,3R,4R).    3-3. Synthesis of (+)-gracilamine by Nagasawa’s group

(+)-Gracilamine (108), isolated from Galanthus gracilis, contains  a  characteristic  pentacyclic  ring  system  (A-E  ring)  with  seven  consecutive  stereogenic  centers,  including  a  quaternary  stereocenter at C3a.[32]  Because of this synthetically challenging  structure,  several  synthetic  studies,  including  total  synthesis,  have  been  reported.[33]    In  our  synthesis,  we  focused  on  the  construction  of  stereochemistry  at  C9a  by  means  of  enantioselective  1,2-type  aza-Friedel-Crafts  reaction  the  presence of guanidine-thiourea bifunctional catalyst 100 (Scheme  11).[34]  Thus, aza-Friedel-Crafts reaction between N-Boc aldimine  For internal use, please do not delete. 4-1. Synthesis of (–)-himalensine A by Dixon’s group  A series of Daphniphyllum alkaloids possess a complex polycyclic  skeleton, and are considered to be active components of the plant,  which  is  used  in  Chinese  herbal  medicine.[37]    Dixon  and  co- workers  reported  a  total  synthesis  of  (–)-himalensine  A  (117)  based on a catalytic, enantioselective prototropic shift/furan Diels- Alder (IMDAF) cascade reaction of 110 (Scheme 12).[38]  In this  cascade  type  of  amide- they  applied  a  new  iminophosphorane  bifunctional  catalyst  109,  and  they  obtained  tricyclic  ketone  111  corresponding  to  the  A/C/D  rings  in  117  in  86%  yield  with  90%  ee.    After  conversion  of  111  into  112,  construction of the B ring under radical cyclization conditions was  conducted  with  followed  by  diastereoselective  hydrogenation  of  112  in  the  presence  of  Crabtree’s  catalyst  to  give  lactam  113  stereoselectively.    Then,  Stetter  cyclization  and  subsequent  isomerization  afforded  thermodynamically  stable  conjugated  enone  116,  which  was  further subjected to selective reduction of amide carbonyl group  to furnish (–)-himalensine A (117). Contiguous  all-carbon  quaternary  stereogenic  centers  are  a  ubiquitous  motif  in  natural  products  and  pharmaceuticals.[39]   Despite  catalytic  enantioselective  in  transformations, construction of the all-carbon quaternary centers  in optically active form is still synthetically challenging.   Recently,  Tu and co-workers reported asymmetric construction of a vicinal  all-carbon  quaternary  stereogenic  center  by  means  of  enantioselective alkylation of bisoxindole 46 in the presence of an  asymmetric  organocatalyst,  and  they  successfully  applied  this  For internal use, please do not delete. reaction  to  a  synthesis  of  (–)-chimonanthidine  (125),  a  dimeric  HPI  alkaloid  (Scheme  13).[40,41]    They  examined  asymmetric  alkylation  of  symmetrical  bis-oxindole  46  in  the  presence  of  spirocyclic  lactam  triazolium  bifunctional  catalyst  118.    Mono  alkylation  of  46  proceeded  upon  addition  of  1  equivalent  of  bromide  119,  and  then  another  bromide  86  was  added  without  quenching  the  first  alkylation  reaction,  affording  the  hetero- dialkylated product 122 in 69% yield with 85% ee (99% ee after a  single  recrystallization).    They  proposed  a  TS  model  involving  both  hydrogen-bonding  and  ion-pairing  interactions  between  catalyst  118  and  the  enolate  of  oxindole  46.  Nucleophilic  alkylation of enolate with alkyl bromide takes place from the less- hindered  side,  avoiding  the  bulky  adamantyl  group.    After  conversion  of  the  Boc  group  to  a  methyl  group,  amidation  and  regioselective reductive cyclization of oxindole moiety in 122 were  carried out to give 123 in 81% yield.  Oxidative cleavage of the  double  bond  followed  by  reductive  amination  and  a  second  reductive cyclization reaction of 123 furnished the characteristic  bis  hexahydropyrroloindole  skeleton.    Finally,  deprotection  of  benzyl group under Perlman conditions gave (–)-chimonanthidine  (125).  Scheme 13. Synthesis of (–)-chimonanthidine by Tu’s group.

This  focus  review  covers  recent  natural  product  syntheses  utilizing  asymmetric  organocatalytic  key  transformations, focusing on bifunctional organocatalysts bearing  a  hydrogen-bonding  donor  group.
